1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,930
This lesson will focus on a few aspects of feature engineering,

2
00:00:03,930 --> 00:00:08,605
which is similar to things you may be familiar with from data wrangling.

3
00:00:08,605 --> 00:00:15,135
In particular, we're going to look at the feature cross and also one-hot encoding.

4
00:00:15,135 --> 00:00:19,260
We're also going to start by looking at a new dataset that

5
00:00:19,260 --> 00:00:23,130
looks at a subsample of taxi rides in New York City.

6
00:00:23,130 --> 00:00:28,140
This dataset comes from the New York City taxi and Limousine Commission and

7
00:00:28,140 --> 00:00:33,375
it's packaged as part of seaborne and can be loaded directly from Jupiter.

8
00:00:33,375 --> 00:00:37,035
You can find all of the other seaborne provided datasets

9
00:00:37,035 --> 00:00:41,245
on seaborne GitHub page. Let's take a look.

10
00:00:41,245 --> 00:00:49,710
We can start by doing our normal imports and then by using seaborne load dataset method.

11
00:00:50,110 --> 00:00:54,635
We see here that this dataset has

12
00:00:54,635 --> 00:01:02,105
6,400 different taxi rides split between 14 different feature columns.

13
00:01:02,105 --> 00:01:04,130
Before we get too far into this,

14
00:01:04,130 --> 00:01:08,675
you may like to take a minute and explore this dataset to get a feel for it.

15
00:01:08,675 --> 00:01:12,170
Now, the feature crosses a broad category of

16
00:01:12,170 --> 00:01:15,710
feature engineering where you combine multiple features.

17
00:01:15,710 --> 00:01:18,815
Often these features are numeric.

18
00:01:18,815 --> 00:01:21,395
For instance, in this case,

19
00:01:21,395 --> 00:01:24,545
we may want to determine the distribution of trips.

20
00:01:24,545 --> 00:01:30,490
We can do that by subtracting the pickup and drop-off times.

21
00:01:30,490 --> 00:01:34,640
Since these are datetime objects will have to convert them to seconds.

22
00:01:34,640 --> 00:01:39,995
We can use the DataFrame d-types method to see that indeed,

23
00:01:39,995 --> 00:01:43,630
pickup and drop-off are both datetime methods.

24
00:01:43,630 --> 00:01:49,640
Here, I'm going to take the difference between the drop-off and pick-up times,

25
00:01:49,640 --> 00:01:51,350
and then I'm going to use

26
00:01:51,350 --> 00:01:55,610
a Lambda function to convert them to the total number of seconds.

27
00:01:55,610 --> 00:02:01,470
Then I'm going to use seaborne to create a histogram of travel time.

28
00:02:03,410 --> 00:02:08,735
Now another thing we might like to do is see how this changes for different boroughs.

29
00:02:08,735 --> 00:02:12,085
Customers can of course go from one borough to another,

30
00:02:12,085 --> 00:02:17,075
so we really only want to look at those that start and stop in the same borough.

31
00:02:17,075 --> 00:02:21,530
Here, I'm going to create a simple series of

32
00:02:21,530 --> 00:02:27,395
true-false values to see if the pickup and drop-off borough are the same.

33
00:02:27,395 --> 00:02:30,800
First, I create a series where I say,

34
00:02:30,800 --> 00:02:34,235
is the drop-off borough the same as the pickup borough.

35
00:02:34,235 --> 00:02:37,760
This will create a series of true and false values that

36
00:02:37,760 --> 00:02:42,035
I then used to create a new feature.

37
00:02:42,035 --> 00:02:47,630
Then I look at only the subset of data with true,

38
00:02:47,630 --> 00:02:49,655
and then look at travel time.

39
00:02:49,655 --> 00:02:54,560
Note, I only use the dataset where trip stayed in the same borough and

40
00:02:54,560 --> 00:03:00,380
then I used hue to look at different ones by color.

41
00:03:00,380 --> 00:03:05,315
Now, although I'm not using the specific feature cross to draw conclusions,

42
00:03:05,315 --> 00:03:11,510
it did help me plot intro-borough travel times very quickly with only two lines of code.

43
00:03:11,510 --> 00:03:15,470
Also, we see that we have a lot more trips in

44
00:03:15,470 --> 00:03:20,075
Manhattan so we should probably look at relative frequencies between them.

45
00:03:20,075 --> 00:03:26,630
We can do this by using the statistics parameter and setting it equal to percent,

46
00:03:26,630 --> 00:03:30,770
and then setting the common norm parameter to false,

47
00:03:30,770 --> 00:03:35,255
meaning that each borough will have its own normalization.

48
00:03:35,255 --> 00:03:39,740
We see here that the distributions look fairly similar.

49
00:03:39,740 --> 00:03:44,450
However, there are very few trips from the Bronx,

50
00:03:44,450 --> 00:03:47,905
so the statistics just to have a lot of outliers.

51
00:03:47,905 --> 00:03:53,975
Lastly, another example of a feature cross is to numerically manipulate features.

52
00:03:53,975 --> 00:03:56,540
For instance, we might want to know if rides with

53
00:03:56,540 --> 00:03:59,975
multiple passengers have different costs or simply,

54
00:03:59,975 --> 00:04:02,185
what is the cost per passenger?

55
00:04:02,185 --> 00:04:05,840
For instance, we can just take the total cost and

56
00:04:05,840 --> 00:04:09,635
divide that by the number of passengers to get the cost per passenger.

57
00:04:09,635 --> 00:04:11,960
Then we can plot this.

58
00:04:11,960 --> 00:04:15,410
Or we might also create a new feature

59
00:04:15,410 --> 00:04:19,325
specifying whether the ride was solo or multi passenger.

60
00:04:19,325 --> 00:04:25,685
Once again, I can use a Lambda function to say if the number of passengers was one,

61
00:04:25,685 --> 00:04:29,690
call it solo, otherwise call it multi passenger.

62
00:04:29,690 --> 00:04:37,145
I can save this into its own series and then quickly use a box plot to show that indeed,

63
00:04:37,145 --> 00:04:39,245
we see that if you travel with friends,

64
00:04:39,245 --> 00:04:43,735
the total cost per person is advantageous on average.

65
00:04:43,735 --> 00:04:47,150
Finally, I would like to introduce one-hot encoding,

66
00:04:47,150 --> 00:04:51,355
which turns a categorical variable into a binary variable.

67
00:04:51,355 --> 00:04:54,335
This means it turns it into a one or zero,

68
00:04:54,335 --> 00:04:56,575
a true or a false.

69
00:04:56,575 --> 00:05:00,485
This is often useful in machine learning contexts,

70
00:05:00,485 --> 00:05:03,815
but you also might see it in data visualization.

71
00:05:03,815 --> 00:05:06,335
To one-hot encode features,

72
00:05:06,335 --> 00:05:11,425
you can use the pandas get dummies method.

73
00:05:11,425 --> 00:05:13,460
If you don't specify a column,

74
00:05:13,460 --> 00:05:16,685
it will operate on all categorical variables.

75
00:05:16,685 --> 00:05:21,125
For instance, if we look at our DataFrame,

76
00:05:21,125 --> 00:05:28,130
will notice that our starting DataFrame has 6,400 rows and 18 features.

77
00:05:28,130 --> 00:05:32,855
But if we just apply get_dummies to the entire DataFrame,

78
00:05:32,855 --> 00:05:38,305
it blows up to now 423 columns.

79
00:05:38,305 --> 00:05:41,150
To get a better idea of what this looks like,

80
00:05:41,150 --> 00:05:44,225
let's just specify the payment column.

81
00:05:44,225 --> 00:05:50,230
Here we see when we pass and get_dummies with our DataFrame and specify that column,

82
00:05:50,230 --> 00:05:55,815
it goes from 18 columns to 19 columns.

83
00:05:55,815 --> 00:05:59,900
Basically, it goes from

84
00:05:59,900 --> 00:06:04,535
payment and then converts it to payment cash or payment credit card,

85
00:06:04,535 --> 00:06:07,520
where if that ride was paid with a credit card,

86
00:06:07,520 --> 00:06:13,020
it will have a zero for cash and a one for credit card, and vice versa.

